Sure! Here's a simple JavaScript program that prints the elements of an array in reverse order:

```javascript
// Define the array
var array = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5];

// Print the original array
console.log("Original array:");
console.log(array);

// Print the array in reverse order
console.log("Reversed array:");
console.log(array.reverse());
```

In this program, we first define an array with some elements. Then, we print the original array using `console.log()`. After that, we use the `reverse()` method to reverse the array in place and print the reversed array.

Note that the `reverse()` method modifies the original array. If you want to keep the original array unchanged, you can create a copy of the array before reversing it:

```javascript
// Define the array
var array = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5];

// Print the original array
console.log("Original array:");
console.log(array);

// Create a copy of the array and reverse it
var reversedArray = array.slice().reverse();

// Print the reversed array
console.log("Reversed array:");
console.log(reversedArray);
```

In this version, we use the `slice()` method to create a copy of the array and then reverse the copy, leaving the original array unchanged.

